Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1. Custom "Cancel" back button + confirmation dialog:**

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="YourApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior Command="{Binding BackCommand}"
                            TextOverride="Cancel" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

**2. Code-behind (or ViewModel) handling:**

```csharp
// EditProductPage.xaml.cs
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

    public EditProductPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BackCommand = new Command(async () => await TryGoBack());
        BindingContext = this;
    }

    private async Task TryGoBack()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!leave) return; // cancel navigation
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }

    // Intercept hardware/Android back button
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () =>
                await TryGoBack());
            return true; // true = cancel default navigation
        }

        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior.TextOverride` replaces the arrow with "Cancel" text.
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` intercepts the Shell back button tap.
- `OnBackButtonPressed()` handles the Android hardware back button (return `true` to cancel).
- iOS swipe-back gesture: set `IconOverride` to a non-null image on `BackButtonBehavior` to disable it, or use `Shell.PresentationMode="ModalAnimated"` for the route.
